Pubic symphysis age was done on sight, although only part of the R symphyseal surface is evident.  It is flat, with no apparent relief, and slight dorsal lipping.  I feel pretty confident in an age assessment of 40-50 years old.

Femur length indicates a subadult around 13-14 years old (male).  Epiphyseal closure puts this subadult around 12-15.  Dental development puts this individual around 15 years old.  See notes in data collection diary.

Based on epiphyseal closure, this subadult was younger than 20, and based on length, older than 5. My best estimation is that this individual was between 6 and 10 years of age (length of ulna).

This individual is about 20.  Tooth eruption difficult to pinpoint because of congenital absence of the M3s.  Sex analysis inconclusive from visual traits of the cranium and pelvis.

Tooth eruption puts this individual around 15 or 16 years old.  Epiphyseal closure puts the individual between 12 and 15.  Because tooth eruption is plus or minus 3 years, I put this individual around 14-16 years.

Cranial meas = F, postcranial = M.  Very few cranial meas, however.  Little to base nonmetric sex assessment on as well.  Dental age is actually about right, probably because this indiv has heavier attrition than most people.
Auricular surface is slightly unclear.  It's somewhere between Phase 5 and Phase 6, so this individual was likely in the range of 41-50.  From what I can see, suture closue is probably in line.
